Biodiversity Loss in Phoenix (2017-2020)

Author

Nathalie Bonnet

Github

https://github.com/NatBonnet/eds220-phoenix-biodiversity

About

Phoenix, AZ has rapidly developed in the past 20 years (Levitt and Eng 2021). This rapid urban growth threatens biodiversity and ecosystem health, urging scientists to examine how development has impacted these areas. The Biodiversity Intactness Index (BII) is an indicator of overall species biodiversity (encompassing number and abundance) in an area (Gassert et al. 2022). Here, BII data was used in tandem with Arizona geographic data to estimate areas of rich biodiversity that experienced significant loss of intactness between 2017 and 2020.

Highlights

  • STAC catalog was used to access Microsoft Planetary Computer collections of BII data
  • xarray and rioxarray libraries were used to transform the file aspects of a geodataframe
  • Negative impacts on biodiversity were assessed numerically and as a visual map

Datasets

  1. 2020 Arizona TIGER shapefile The shapefile for Arizona geographic data was accessed from data.gov and used to reference Phoenix's spatial boundary.

Data.gov. (2021). TIGER/Line Shapefile, 2020, State, Arizona, Census Tracts [Dataset]. https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/tiger-line-shapefile-2020-state-arizona-census-tracts

  1. Biodiversity Intactness Index Data (2017-2020) Microsoft Planetary Computer STAC API contains spatiotemporal metadata with Earth science datasets. BII collections contained from the Phoenix area were retireved from the catalog, returning 4 items from 2017-2020.

Microsoft Planetary Computer STAC API. (2017-2020). BII catalog data [Catalog]

References

Z. Levitt and J. Eng, Where Americas developed areas are growing: Way off into the horizon, The Washington Post, Aug. 2021, Available: https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/interactive/2021/land-development-urban-growth-maps/. [Accessed: Nov. 22, 2024]

F. Gassert, J. Mazzarello, and S. Hyde, Global 100m Projections of Biodiversity Intactness for the years 2017-2020 [Technical Whitepaper]. Aug. 2022. Available: https://ai4edatasetspublicassets.blob.core.windows.net/assets/pdfs/io-biodiversity/Biodiversity_Intactness_whitepaper.pdf

Setup and cleaning

Importing libraries necessary to work with geopandas, xarray and rioxarray, and visualization,

Arizona shapefile data was accessed as a geopandas.GeoDataFrame and the column names are standardized using str.lower to convert all names to lower case.

In[4]:
# Load in phoenix dataset
fp = os.path.join("data", "tl_2024_04_cousub", "tl_2024_04_cousub.shp")
arizona = gpd.read_file(fp)

# Clean names of columns for easier subsetting 
arizona.columns = arizona.columns.str.lower()

Here we access STAC (SpatioTemporal Asset) Catalog) API with pystac_client to retrieve the Microsoft Planetary Computer (MPC) collections.

In[3]:
# Open planetary computer catalog
catalog = Client.open(
    "https://planetarycomputer.microsoft.com/api/stac/v1",
    modifier=planetary_computer.sign_inplace,
)

# Access collections within planetary computer catalog
catalog.get_collections()

# Retrieve listed collections
collections = list(catalog.get_collections())

Now we can search for relevant objects to the analysis from MPC collections by specify ing desired bounding coordinates for Phoenix subdivision area and timeframe. Here, we specify the collection name that we want to look into with "io-biodiversity" to access BII data.

In[5]:
# Specify bbox for Phoenix
bbox = [-112.826843, 32.974108, -111.184387, 33.863574]

# Specify time range of interest
time_range = "2017-01-01/2020-01-01"

# Search with given parameters for bii data
search = catalog.search(
    collections = ["io-biodiversity"], 
    bbox = bbox, 
    datetime = time_range
)

Because we specified the time range as 2017-2020, we expect to get 4 objects out of this search because MPC data is generally organized by year.

In[]:
# Get the items returned from the catalog search 
items = search.item_collection()

Now that we have the items within the time range, we want to select data from the year 2017 and 2020 by indexing into the list of items and opening the data objects to compare the change in biodiversity intactness index between the two years.

In[7]:
# Store items with corresponding year
ph_2017 = items[3]
ph_2020 = items[0]

# Retrieve data from item assets
bio_data_2017 = planetary_computer.sign(ph_2017.assets['data'].href)
bio_data_2020 = planetary_computer.sign(ph_2020.assets['data'].href)

# Open raster information from objects
biodiv_2017 = rioxr.open_rasterio(bio_data_2017)
biodiv_2020 = rioxr.open_rasterio(bio_data_2020)

Now that we have properly retrieved the biodiversity index data from STAC, we will check the Arizona data to confirm what we are working with.

BII Analysis for Phoenix Subdivision

Now with the Phoenix geometries, we are interested in quantifying and visualizing the change in diodiveristy in the area between 2017 and 2020. The first step in analysis is to clip diodiversity data for both years to only the Phoenix area, which effectively sets the areas outside the cells contained by phoenix.geometry to NA.

In[]:
# Create clipped biodiversity observations within Phoenix area
phoenix_bbox = phoenix.total_bounds
clip_2017 = biodiv_2017.rio.clip_box(*bbox).rio.clip(phoenix.geometry)
clip_2020 = biodiv_2020.rio.clip_box(*bbox).rio.clip(phoenix.geometry)

Here we can map biodiversity observations for the first year (2017) to confirm that the extent of the masked raster looks the same as our Phoenix Subdivision.

In[49]:
# Visualize where bii data is being clipped to
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
# Plot 2017 observations
clip_2017.plot(ax=ax, cmap = "Reds", alpha = 0.5, cbar_kwargs = {'location':'bottom', 'label':'BII for 2017'})
# Set title
# Add basemap using contextily
ctx.add_basemap(ax, source=ctx.providers.OpenStreetMap.Mapnik, crs = phoenix.crs)
ax.set_title("Phoenix BII values from 2017")
# Remove axes
ax.axis('off')
plt.show()

Compared to the Phoenix Subdivision area, this looks to have the same extent on the basemap.

Now we can move forward with calculating biodviersity loss between years of interest. Here, we create a raster of boolean arguments for whether or not the given cell value is as high or greater than a BII value of 0.75. Raster cells with BII values equal to or above 0.75 will return as 'True', and any below those high biodiversity sites will be categorized as 'False'

In[19]:
# Use boolean argument to reclassify cells
bii_2017 = clip_2017 >= 0.75
bii_2020 = clip_2020 >= 0.75

Using these cells, we calculate the percentage of high biodiversity areas (>= 0.75) in Phoenix between 2017 and 2020 by dividing the number of cells returning "True" by the total number of cells in our clipped Phoenix area data, which excludes any values outside the boundary.

In[20]:
# Find the percentage of area in Phoenix with a biodiversity index value of 0.75 or greater in 2017
perc_2017 = bii_2017.sum()/clip_2017.count()*100
print(f"Percent of high biodiversity area in Phoenix in 2017: {np.array(perc_2017).tolist():.2f}%")

Percent of high biodiversity area in Phoenix in 2017: 7.13%
In[22]:
perc_2020 = bii_2020.sum()/clip_2020.count()*100
print(f"Percent of high biodiversity area in Phoenix in 2020: {np.array(perc_2020).tolist():.2f}%")

Percent of high biodiversity area in Phoenix in 2020: 6.49%

Visualizing BII change between 2017 and 2020 in Phoenix

We can now visualize areas that lost areas of high biodiversity between 2017 and 2020.

To plot only the areas that changed from BII 0.75 to less, we need to convert the boolean arguments in our biodiverstity raster to to numeric binaries (0,1).

In[23]:
# Convert boolean values to binary arguments
bii_2017_int = bii_2017.astype(int)
bii_2020_int = bii_2020.astype(int)

Then, the difference between areas is calculated by subtracting 2020 values from 2017. Conceptually, we now want to visualize values with a change between years, so we can subset the result for only nonzero value cells. From here, the decrease in biodiversity is plotted.

In[50]:
bii_chng = bii_2017_int - bii_2020_int
bii_chng = bii_chng.where(bii_chng != 0)

In the final visualization, it was necessary to add a legend patch value to indicate areas that had a decrease in high areas of biodiversity. This was possible with the matplotlib.patches patch function to specify the visuals. This is applied to the ax.legend element to add it onto the plot with the color bar.

In[26]:
# Add patch and label indicating change area meaning
legend_elements = [patch.Patch(facecolor='red', edgecolor='r', label='Area with BII  0.75 lost from 2017 to 2020')]

# Plot 2017 biodiversity values against areas that had a signficant decrease
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10,10))
ax.axis("off")
clip_2020.plot(ax=ax, cmap ="Greens", cbar_kwargs = {'location':'bottom', 'label':'BII for 2020'})
bii_chng.plot(ax=ax, cmap = "bwr", add_colorbar = False)
ax.legend(handles=legend_elements, 
loc="upper center", bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.05), ncol=5)
# Labels, title, and legend
ax.set_ylabel(" ")
ax.set_title("Biodiversity Intactness Index (BII) Phoenix Subdivision",
             {'fontsize':15})

plt.show()

Out of interest, a contrasting plot to visualize any areas with positive change between overall BII values was created. This took the overall difference between rasters and plotted the increase or decrease across the raster.

In[52]:
# Take difference in rasters 2017-2020
diff_clip = clip_2017 - clip_2020

# Plot difference raster
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10,10))
ax.axis("off")
diff_clip.plot(ax=ax, cmap ="YlOrRd", alpha = 0.7, cbar_kwargs = {'location':'bottom', 'label':'BII difference between 2017 and 2020'})
bii_chng.plot(ax=ax, cmap = "bwr" , add_colorbar = False)
# Add basemap using contextily
ctx.add_basemap(ax, source=ctx.providers.OpenStreetMap.Mapnik, crs = arizona.crs)
ax.legend(handles=legend_elements, 
loc="upper center", bbox_to_anchor=(0.3, -0.05), ncol=5)
# Labels, title, and legend
ax.set_ylabel(" ")
ax.set_title("Difference in Biodiversity Intactness Index (BII) Values from 2017-2020 in Phoenix Subdivision",
             {'fontsize':10})

plt.show()

Discussion

From the calculation of the percentages of total area in Phoenix with BII greater than or equal to 0.75, we know that the percent of area at this high level of biodviersity went down in the urban area. The difference was about 0.4%. To compare the area with the total change in biodiversity, the difference of index values was plotted between years with the areas of interest overlaid on the basemap of the Phoenix area. Interestingly, we can see that the areas of land that experienced biodiversity loss were within or near a regional park and preserve area. Though we were interested in the negative effects of urbanization, comparing these areas with overall index value change across the area shows that the biodiversity in some areas increased, most noteably in the Western edge of the Phoenix area near large urban areas. It is unclear from the data alone what may have led to this pattern. However, it might be that in areas with greater reported biodiversity there were simply more reported species observations with an increase in residents. Further exploration into the data collection process would potentially yield better insight into the data.
